  <section id="about">
    <h2>What are Semantic Tags?</h2>
    <p>
      Semantic tags clearly describe their meaning in a human- and machine-readable way.
      They make HTML more understandable for developers, browsers, and search engines.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Articles section -->
  <section id="articles">
    <h2>Examples of Semantic Tags</h2>

    <!-- Article 1 -->
    <article>
      <h3>&lt;article&gt;</h3>
      <p>
        The <code>&lt;article&gt;</code> tag represents independent content.
        For example, a blog post, a news article, or a forum post.
      </p>
    </article>

    <!-- Article 2 -->
    <article>
      <h3>&lt;section&gt;</h3>
      <p>
        The <code>&lt;section&gt;</code> tag defines a thematic grouping of content, usually with a heading.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <!-- Aside: Represents side content -->
  <aside>
    <h3>Did You Know?</h3>
    <p>
      Before HTML5, developers mostly used <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> tags everywhere.
      Semantic tags replaced many of them to make code more meaningful!
    </p>
  </aside>

